  "response_text": "A plain light background appears with centered black text reading, “A small miracle for colors.” The words remain for a moment, then the screen darkens.\n\nA staged laundry-room scene appears with a nautical feel. A middle-aged, balding man with a mustache and glasses stands behind a small white table or podium. He wears a dark double-breasted blazer with a crest badge, a white shirt, a red bow tie, and light-colored trousers, suggesting a yacht-club or ship’s officer style. Behind him are two washing machines, one on each side, and a round porthole on the wall showing blue sky and water. On the table in front of him are two detergent bottles: a red-orange bottle on his left and a blue Cheer bottle on his right. A bright signal flag hangs to his left, divided into a reddish-pink top half and a yellow bottom half.\n\nThe man turns toward the hanging flag and begins handling it like a signalman. He reaches up, lifts and folds the red-and-yellow cloth, then holds a small pennant-shaped piece in front of his chest. The flag has a V-shaped notch cut from the bottom edge, with red or pink across the top and yellow below. He briefly presents it, then moves it aside. He picks up another similar flag from the line, using his hands near the top edge as if removing it or preparing it for washing. He again holds the flag up squarely between the two detergent bottles, then tosses it toward the side.\n\nHe then gestures between the two washing machines and the two bottles, visually setting up a comparison. He opens or lowers the large gray lids or panels on both machines, first on the left side near the red-orange bottle, then on the right side near the blue Cheer bottle. The two washers sit behind the table, their control panels visible once the lids are lowered. He returns to the center, standing between the bottles with a composed, demonstrator-like posture.\n\nThe scene darkens briefly, then reappears with the man holding a long brass spyglass or telescope to one eye, pointed toward the porthole. Large white text at the bottom reads, “15 washes.” The red-orange bottle remains on the left side of the table and the blue Cheer bottle on the right. He continues looking through the telescope, then lowers and collapses it in front of him, reinforcing the idea that time or many wash cycles have passed.\n\nAfter another brief dark transition, the man stands centered again with large white text at the bottom reading, “25 washes later.” He reaches down on both sides and lifts two matching signal flags, one from the left side near the red-orange bottle and one from the right side near the blue Cheer bottle. Holding them side by side, he shows a clear difference: the left flag is badly faded, with the top now pale pink and the bottom nearly washed out to off-white; the right flag still has a strong reddish-pink top and a bright yellow bottom. He looks down at the flags, then forward, keeping them aligned so the comparison is easy to see.\n\nIn a closer view, his hands grip the top edges of the two cloth flags. The left, faded flag is labeled on screen “A leading liquid,” while the right, brighter flag is labeled “Ultra liquid Cheer.” Small text near the lower left reads “100% cotton.” The left flag’s colors look weak and uneven, especially the yellow area, while the right flag remains much more vivid. The two flags still have the same V-shaped notch at the bottom, making the color difference the main visible contrast.\n\nThe final view focuses on the product. A large blue Cheer bottle with a white cap stands at the back, its label showing the bold word “cheer” over vertical rainbow color bars. A smaller blue bottle is placed in front by a hand, and its label reads “Ultra Liquid Cheer,” again with the colorful rainbow design. A folded red-and-yellow signal flag lies on the surface beneath the bottles. As the smaller bottle is set in place, white text appears on the left: “Dirt goes. Color stays.” The two blue Cheer bottles remain prominent, with the smaller Ultra Liquid Cheer bottle in front as the featured product.",
